WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.240
[Amit Varma]: I've always believed in the principle that two consenting adults have the right to engage

00:00:11.240 --> 00:00:16.580
[Amit Varma]: in any voluntary transaction as long as it does not infringe on the rights of any other

00:00:16.580 --> 00:00:22.120
[Amit Varma]: individual and I believe this to be true whether that interaction takes place in the bedroom

00:00:22.120 --> 00:00:24.280
[Amit Varma]: or in the marketplace.

00:00:24.280 --> 00:00:29.360
[Amit Varma]: One of the saddest things about the way ideologies are formed in our modern times is that personal

00:00:29.360 --> 00:00:34.600
[Amit Varma]: freedoms and economic freedoms are treated as two separate things but I believe that

00:00:34.600 --> 00:00:41.400
[Amit Varma]: they are at their heart the exact same right and the exact same expression of our autonomy

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:42.960
[Amit Varma]: as human beings.

00:00:42.960 --> 00:00:47.600
[Amit Varma]: Many people especially on the left give personal freedoms such as the freedom of speech the

00:00:47.600 --> 00:00:53.320
[Amit Varma]: respect they deserve but not so much economic freedom and it is often vice versa on the

00:00:53.320 --> 00:00:58.860
[Amit Varma]: right and in India these distinctions of left and right don't really apply and most political

00:00:58.860 --> 00:01:03.200
[Amit Varma]: parties don't give either kind of freedom the respect they deserve.

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:09.560
[Amit Varma]: It is the worst of both worlds and a particularly telling illustration of this is the way India

00:01:09.560 --> 00:01:27.740
[Unknown]: treats its street vendors.

00:01:27.740 --> 00:01:29.140
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:01:29.140 --> 00:01:35.300
[Amit Varma]: The Indian state's core function should be to be a protector of its citizens but instead

00:01:35.300 --> 00:01:38.900
[Amit Varma]: it is most often a predator and a parasite.

00:01:38.900 --> 00:01:43.080
[Amit Varma]: Nowhere is this more apparent than in the case of street vendors.

00:01:43.080 --> 00:01:46.900
[Amit Varma]: People sell on the streets because people want to buy from them.

00:01:46.900 --> 00:01:52.580
[Amit Varma]: Every voluntary transaction leaves both parties better off and so society benefits from this

00:01:52.580 --> 00:01:59.180
[Amit Varma]: exchange and yet our street vendors are routinely harassed and exploited and preyed upon and

00:01:59.180 --> 00:02:01.820
[Amit Varma]: are often too powerless to fight back.

00:02:01.820 --> 00:02:06.700
[Amit Varma]: My guest today to speak on this subject is Prashant Narang, a lawyer and legal expert

00:02:06.700 --> 00:02:11.340
[Amit Varma]: who works at the Center for Civil Society in Delhi which has fought for the rights of

00:02:11.340 --> 00:02:15.700
[Amit Varma]: street vendors in India for many, many years.

00:02:15.700 --> 00:02:23.540
[Amit Varma]: Before we begin our conversation though, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:02:23.540 --> 00:02:28.700
[Amit Varma]: Are you one of those people who not only loves to read but also wants to write better?

00:02:28.700 --> 00:02:30.700
[Amit Varma]: If so, I have something for you.

00:02:30.700 --> 00:02:36.140
[Amit Varma]: Since April this year, I've been teaching an online course called the art of clear writing.

00:02:36.140 --> 00:02:40.180
[Amit Varma]: Our webinars spread out over four Saturdays in which I share whatever I've learnt about

00:02:40.180 --> 00:02:44.860
[Amit Varma]: the craft and practice of writing over 25 years as a professional writer.

00:02:44.860 --> 00:02:50.940
[Amit Varma]: The course also contains many writing exercises, discussions on email and WhatsApp and much

00:02:50.940 --> 00:02:52.180
[Amit Varma]: interactivity.

00:02:52.180 --> 00:02:55.720
[Amit Varma]: It costs rupees 10,000 or 150 dollars.

00:02:55.720 --> 00:03:00.180
[Amit Varma]: You can check out the details at indiancut.com slash clear writing.

00:03:00.180 --> 00:03:01.680
[Amit Varma]: This link will be in the show notes.

00:03:01.680 --> 00:03:04.860
[Amit Varma]: If you want to bridge the gap between the thoughts in your head and the words on the

00:03:04.860 --> 00:03:08.820
[Amit Varma]: page, then the art of clear writing might be just what you need.

00:03:08.820 --> 00:03:11.780
[Amit Varma]: July batches begin on Saturday, July 4th.

00:03:11.780 --> 00:03:17.660
[Amit Varma]: So hurry and register before then at indiancut.com slash clear writing.

00:03:17.660 --> 00:03:23.660
[Amit Varma]: Prashant, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:03:23.660 --> 00:03:24.660
[Amit Varma]: Thanks Amit.

00:03:24.660 --> 00:03:28.700
[Amit Varma]: So Prashant, you know, before we sort of get to the subject at hand, tell me a little bit

00:03:28.700 --> 00:03:31.100
[Guest]: about your journey.

00:03:31.100 --> 00:03:37.740
[Guest]: My journey, I am a first generation lawyer, but also a first generation graduate.

00:03:37.740 --> 00:03:44.180
[Guest]: And I come from a family of traders, you know, family of retailers.

00:03:44.180 --> 00:03:52.220
[Guest]: My family is also a family of Punjabi refugees, grandparents migrated from, you know, some

00:03:52.220 --> 00:03:56.660
[Guest]: parts of Pakistan in 47, 48.

00:03:56.660 --> 00:04:03.980
[Guest]: Prashant was really a partition child, because he was born here, but probably conceived there.

00:04:03.980 --> 00:04:12.860
[Guest]: And you know, I come from that kind of a family where daughters are more educated than sons.

00:04:12.860 --> 00:04:17.140
[Guest]: And most of my cousins barely finished their schooling.

00:04:17.140 --> 00:04:24.100
[Guest]: And for me to take that step, you know, take that decision to go to college and take up

00:04:24.100 --> 00:04:29.500
[Guest]: a vocational course or even then think about law.

00:04:29.500 --> 00:04:33.820
[Guest]: So law was something that I'd never thought before.

00:04:33.820 --> 00:04:39.460
[Guest]: And I did a professional course after my 12th, and then joined Dad's business, you know,

00:04:39.460 --> 00:04:41.780
[Guest]: departmental store.

00:04:41.780 --> 00:04:48.060
[Guest]: And it was only in 2005-06, I was thinking of doing some sort of masters, I was not too

00:04:48.060 --> 00:04:49.740
[Guest]: sure what.

00:04:49.740 --> 00:04:53.020
[Guest]: And I ended up attending a CCS seminar on public policy.

00:04:53.020 --> 00:04:56.940
[Guest]: I wasn't too sure of, you know, what it will be about.

00:04:56.940 --> 00:05:01.380
[Guest]: But there, you know, someone suggested to me that I should think about law and I'll

00:05:01.380 --> 00:05:02.660
[Guest]: be a good lawyer.

00:05:02.660 --> 00:05:09.780
[Guest]: I don't think whether, you know, I was really not sure whether I should, I should not.

00:05:09.780 --> 00:05:14.740
[Guest]: But I prepared for the entrance exam and I got admission in Delhi University, age was

00:05:14.740 --> 00:05:16.180
[Guest]: no bar for Delhi University.

00:05:16.180 --> 00:05:20.800
[Guest]: That's one of very few places, you know, you can join law at any age.

00:05:20.800 --> 00:05:22.200
[Guest]: So that happened.

00:05:22.200 --> 00:05:27.340
[Guest]: It was only in my first semester, I realized that I loved law so much.

00:05:27.340 --> 00:05:32.060
[Guest]: You know, it was a similar feeling what you saw probably on Amir Khan's face in Three

00:05:32.060 --> 00:05:35.580
[Guest]: Idiots movie when I was sitting in the engineering class.

00:05:35.580 --> 00:05:40.980
[Guest]: So that kind of enjoyment and, you know, the feeling of joy I had.

00:05:40.980 --> 00:05:44.940
[Guest]: I love my constitutional law classes, jurisprudence classes.

00:05:44.940 --> 00:05:46.860
[Guest]: So that's how it happened.

00:05:46.860 --> 00:05:54.040
[Guest]: But in terms of other influences, you know, life has been set of contrasts.

00:05:54.040 --> 00:05:56.660
[Guest]: So I have been into two kinds of schools.

00:05:56.660 --> 00:06:02.420
[Guest]: One is a missionary school, but also a school run by Sangh RSS.

00:06:02.420 --> 00:06:10.300
[Guest]: The other set of contrast is I have been in JNU, but also in Center for Civil Society.

00:06:10.300 --> 00:06:12.600
[Guest]: I worked there.

00:06:12.600 --> 00:06:20.080
[Guest]: The next set of contrast is that I studied law in a state run university, Delhi University,

00:06:20.080 --> 00:06:26.560
[Guest]: but also in a very elite private university, Jindal Global Law School.

00:06:26.560 --> 00:06:31.640
[Guest]: And these are the diverse experiences that influenced and shaped my journey.

00:06:31.640 --> 00:06:35.760
[Amit Varma]: And it also strikes me that, you know, like you said, you came from a family of traders

00:06:35.760 --> 00:06:41.240
[Amit Varma]: and you were a trader at one point yourself where you were helping your dad with his business.

00:06:41.240 --> 00:06:47.560
[Amit Varma]: And the thought that comes to mind is that, did that then shape very crucially how you

00:06:47.560 --> 00:06:49.480
[Amit Varma]: look at the law and the constitution?

00:06:49.480 --> 00:06:54.720
[Amit Varma]: Because it seems to me that there is a danger in people who are born among the elites, who

00:06:54.720 --> 00:06:58.640
[Amit Varma]: are then, you know, live an elite life, go abroad, and, you know, do law at Columbia

00:06:58.640 --> 00:07:02.480
[Amit Varma]: or wherever, and they come back, and they are looking at the constitution in a very

00:07:02.480 --> 00:07:10.560
[Amit Varma]: theoretical framework, upar upar se, whereas you actually have a better lived idea of how

00:07:10.560 --> 00:07:16.440
[Amit Varma]: laws intersect with the everyday daily lives of citizens.

00:07:16.440 --> 00:07:19.560
[Amit Varma]: Would you say that that's sort of a factor in shaping you?

00:07:19.560 --> 00:07:25.520
[Guest]: I couldn't agree more, because you see Rohit Dey's book, People's Constitution, for the

00:07:25.520 --> 00:07:31.440
[Guest]: first time, we, you know, have a book that documents the struggles of, you know, people

00:07:31.440 --> 00:07:38.280
[Guest]: at the bottom of the pyramid, their struggles and how they use the constitution.

00:07:38.280 --> 00:07:43.080
[Guest]: And I don't find it surprising that most of the stories are about economic freedom, you

00:07:43.080 --> 00:07:47.080
[Guest]: know, about their struggles with earning their livelihood.

00:07:47.080 --> 00:07:51.400
[Guest]: Not a single story there is about freedom of speech and expression or about other fundamental

00:07:51.400 --> 00:07:52.400
[Guest]: rights.

00:07:52.400 --> 00:07:53.800
[Amit Varma]: It's all about economic freedom.

00:07:53.800 --> 00:07:59.560
[Amit Varma]: It's almost like in the minds of many people, there's almost like this frightening disconnect,

00:07:59.560 --> 00:08:03.240
[Amit Varma]: where they will support freedom when it comes to personal freedoms, like the freedom of

00:08:03.240 --> 00:08:04.760
[Amit Varma]: speech and so on.

00:08:04.760 --> 00:08:09.040
[Amit Varma]: But they will not understand that the same freedom should apply to all interactions two

00:08:09.040 --> 00:08:10.240
[Amit Varma]: people have with each other.

00:08:10.240 --> 00:08:15.240
[Amit Varma]: So if we are two consenting adults, it should have the same moral value if someone stops

00:08:15.240 --> 00:08:20.240
[Amit Varma]: us either from sleeping with each other, or from trading in the marketplace.

00:08:20.240 --> 00:08:25.280
[Amit Varma]: And there's a certain kind of left liberal view that voluntary action is to be respected

00:08:25.280 --> 00:08:29.440
[Amit Varma]: as it should be if it is happening in a bedroom and it's a personal interaction, but not if

00:08:29.440 --> 00:08:33.080
[Amit Varma]: it's in the marketplace, where suddenly it becomes something entirely different and their

00:08:33.080 --> 00:08:36.280
[Amit Varma]: coercion is justified, intervention is justified.

00:08:36.280 --> 00:08:41.280
[Amit Varma]: And that's almost, in a sense, written into the DNA of our constitution and our laws,

00:08:41.280 --> 00:08:45.160
[Amit Varma]: where some freedoms are respected more than others, while all of them arise essentially

00:08:45.160 --> 00:08:46.320
[Amit Varma]: from the same source.

00:08:46.320 --> 00:08:47.320
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:08:47.320 --> 00:08:48.320
[Guest]: I agree.

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:55.600
[Guest]: I think for them, I mean, for left liberals, the sense of morality and legality differs

00:08:55.600 --> 00:08:57.720
[Amit Varma]: for personal freedom and for economic freedom.

00:08:57.720 --> 00:08:58.720
[Amit Varma]: Yep.

00:08:58.720 --> 00:09:02.200
[Amit Varma]: So one of the things which you're obviously, you've been involved deeply in and which we're

00:09:02.200 --> 00:09:06.880
[Amit Varma]: talking about now in this episode is sort of street vendors, which is something the

00:09:06.880 --> 00:09:10.960
[Amit Varma]: Center for Civil Society, where you work now and have worked for many, many years has been

00:09:10.960 --> 00:09:12.800
[Amit Varma]: involved with for a long time.

00:09:12.800 --> 00:09:18.760
[Amit Varma]: So tell me sort of how you got to, you know, this specific subject, per se, and what were

00:09:18.760 --> 00:09:21.640
[Amit Varma]: your early learnings from it, interactions with it?

00:09:21.640 --> 00:09:28.880
[Guest]: Actually, during my law school, I never took up any internship with any law firm.

00:09:28.880 --> 00:09:35.120
[Guest]: And I was looking at the issue of auto rickshaw drivers in Delhi.

00:09:35.120 --> 00:09:39.920
[Guest]: And, you know, there were different kinds of policy responses to the problem of auto

00:09:39.920 --> 00:09:40.920
[Guest]: rickshaw driver.

00:09:40.920 --> 00:09:44.680
[Guest]: The problem was, commuters often complain that they don't go by meter.

00:09:44.680 --> 00:09:47.880
[Guest]: And policy response was that we need to discipline them.

00:09:47.880 --> 00:09:54.400
[Guest]: How you discipline them is either you have a digital meter, you have workshop for them,

00:09:54.400 --> 00:10:00.880
[Guest]: you prescribe a uniform for them, they have to have GPS, and so on and so forth.

00:10:00.880 --> 00:10:04.920
[Guest]: And at times, you know, you hear, and you read in the newspapers that there is a cultural

00:10:04.920 --> 00:10:08.760
[Guest]: issue, they are migrants, they don't know how to behave with commuters, so on and so

00:10:08.760 --> 00:10:09.760
[Guest]: forth.

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:15.680
[Guest]: So, while I was in law college, I with my other friends, we investigated, we did some

00:10:15.680 --> 00:10:22.120
[Guest]: research and found out that it was more a policy issue, because of the disparity between

00:10:22.120 --> 00:10:23.720
[Guest]: demand and supply.

00:10:23.720 --> 00:10:27.240
[Guest]: And there was a permit system, the government didn't issue any further permits.

00:10:27.240 --> 00:10:29.360
[Guest]: So, this was one issue that we studied.

00:10:29.360 --> 00:10:34.120
[Guest]: And we, you know, made a documentary called third wheel, a shorter version of this documentary

00:10:34.120 --> 00:10:37.880
[Guest]: still available on YouTube, it's called third wheel.

00:10:37.880 --> 00:10:44.280
[Guest]: Right after finishing my LLB, I joined a lawyer, Miss Indira Unnayar.

00:10:44.280 --> 00:10:52.520
[Guest]: And I assisted her in another public interest matter, which was about cycle rickshaw pullers.

00:10:52.520 --> 00:10:58.240
[Guest]: And same issue, very similar, there was a permit issue, you know, fixed number of permits

00:10:58.240 --> 00:11:00.800
[Guest]: and the government didn't issue further permits.

00:11:00.800 --> 00:11:04.120
[Guest]: And the number of permit was limited to 99,000.

00:11:04.120 --> 00:11:08.080
[Guest]: But there were actually 6 lakh cycle rickshaw pullers in Delhi, which meant more than 5

00:11:08.080 --> 00:11:10.720
[Guest]: lakh cycle rickshaw pullers were illegal.

00:11:10.720 --> 00:11:15.960
[Guest]: And that give an opportunity to the municipal officials, traffic police to basically seek

00:11:15.960 --> 00:11:16.960
[Guest]: rent.

00:11:16.960 --> 00:11:23.320
[Guest]: So, on 10th of February 2010, Delhi High Court decided in favor of cycle rickshaw pullers.

00:11:23.320 --> 00:11:28.520
[Guest]: And basically, you know, the so called mafia became entrepreneurs.

00:11:28.520 --> 00:11:30.760
[Guest]: And I found that really very interesting.

00:11:30.760 --> 00:11:35.320
[Guest]: That was around the same time CCS was probably doing Jeevika campaign related to street vendors

00:11:35.320 --> 00:11:37.040
[Guest]: in Rajasthan.

00:11:37.040 --> 00:11:39.240
[Guest]: I took up masters after that.

00:11:39.240 --> 00:11:45.800
[Guest]: And it was only in 2013 that I joined CCS, CCS was already doing street vendors project

00:11:45.800 --> 00:11:46.800
[Guest]: by then.

00:11:46.800 --> 00:11:52.840
[Guest]: And they had an office in Jaipur, Rajasthan, and the street vendor associations knew them

00:11:52.840 --> 00:11:54.680
[Guest]: quite well.

00:11:54.680 --> 00:12:01.680
[Guest]: So there was a PIL pending before these High Court of Rajasthan with respect to this issue.

00:12:01.680 --> 00:12:07.720
[Guest]: And Rajasthan passed a state law for protection of street vendors, but it was totally a toothless

00:12:07.720 --> 00:12:08.720
[Guest]: law.

00:12:08.720 --> 00:12:13.080
[Guest]: A lot of other organizations as well as street vendor organizations were advocating for a

00:12:13.080 --> 00:12:14.360
[Guest]: central law.

00:12:14.360 --> 00:12:20.120
[Guest]: And if you remember, UP had a National Advisory Council, they began to have consultations,

00:12:20.120 --> 00:12:23.920
[Guest]: I think in right from 2009, 2010.

00:12:23.920 --> 00:12:27.040
[Guest]: And finally, the Central Act came in 2014.

00:12:27.040 --> 00:12:31.240
[Guest]: Also the Supreme Court passed its orders and asked, you know, the Parliament, I mean, the

00:12:31.240 --> 00:12:36.440
[Guest]: Supreme Court asking the Parliament to come up with a law, a federal law to tackle a municipal

00:12:36.440 --> 00:12:38.560
[Guest]: level subject.

00:12:38.560 --> 00:12:46.120
[Guest]: So these were my experiences with livelihoods of urban poor and similar issues, be it auto

00:12:46.120 --> 00:12:50.240
[Guest]: rickshaw drivers, be it cycle rickshaw pullers, or be it street vendors.

00:12:50.240 --> 00:12:55.960
[Guest]: The issue is state harassment, you know, the harassment caused by police, by municipal

00:12:55.960 --> 00:13:00.400
[Guest]: officials and permit and license against at the core of it.

00:13:00.400 --> 00:13:04.680
[Amit Varma]: So you know, before we get down into the nitty gritties of the problems that street vendors

00:13:04.680 --> 00:13:09.240
[Amit Varma]: face and all of that one sort of final broad question, which is also about something that

00:13:09.240 --> 00:13:12.920
[Amit Varma]: you mentioned, you know, a brief while ago about the economic way of thinking.

00:13:12.920 --> 00:13:18.040
[Amit Varma]: And is it the case that like when you describe the cycle rickshaw pullers in Bombay and all

00:13:18.040 --> 00:13:22.120
[Amit Varma]: the policy responses, which were all horrible, and all the other popular sort of responses

00:13:22.120 --> 00:13:24.720
[Amit Varma]: people had to that which are equally horrible.

00:13:24.720 --> 00:13:28.880
[Amit Varma]: And the key thing that they're missing there, obviously, is that people respond to incentives.

00:13:28.880 --> 00:13:33.000
[Amit Varma]: And if you have a system where the incentives are absolutely horrible, then everyone will

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:35.680
[Amit Varma]: behave rationally, and you'll get really bad outcomes.

00:13:35.680 --> 00:13:40.160
[Amit Varma]: For example, if you have your x number of rickshaw pullers, but you're giving licenses,

00:13:40.160 --> 00:13:44.200
[Amit Varma]: which are point 2x, then obviously, you will have that rent seeking, you will have bribery

00:13:44.200 --> 00:13:47.040
[Amit Varma]: and the cost for society go up massively.

00:13:47.040 --> 00:13:52.240
[Amit Varma]: So has that been like, it seems to me that that's a fundamental challenge at the core

00:13:52.240 --> 00:13:58.000
[Amit Varma]: of either making government work well, or even how we look at other issues in isolation,

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:03.760
[Amit Varma]: be it the constitution or legality itself, that people don't understand this fundamental,

00:14:03.760 --> 00:14:07.360
[Amit Varma]: and I won't even call it the economic way of thinking, because that seems to imply that

00:14:07.360 --> 00:14:10.760
[Amit Varma]: there is something niche about it, which doesn't apply to everything.

00:14:10.760 --> 00:14:15.680
[Amit Varma]: Because economics is a study of human behavior, we all obviously respond to incentives.

00:14:15.680 --> 00:14:18.160
[Amit Varma]: And that's a fundamental fact you have to take into account.

00:14:18.160 --> 00:14:21.880
[Amit Varma]: And if you don't, none of your other thinking or intervention will work.

00:14:21.880 --> 00:14:26.960
[Amit Varma]: So has that been a big challenge with you both in terms of changing mindsets, and then

00:14:26.960 --> 00:14:28.920
[Amit Varma]: in terms of actually getting things done?

00:14:28.920 --> 00:14:29.920
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:14:29.920 --> 00:14:30.920
[Guest]: You're right.

00:14:30.920 --> 00:14:37.320
[Guest]: Because if you look at the judgments related to cycle rickshaw pullers, or street vendors,

00:14:37.320 --> 00:14:42.160
[Guest]: you know, especially in 80s, I would say 50s and 60s were not that bad.

00:14:42.160 --> 00:14:50.520
[Guest]: The judges did what they were supposed to, but it was in 80s that you see the problems

00:14:50.520 --> 00:14:51.520
[Guest]: in the judgment.

00:14:51.520 --> 00:14:55.200
[Guest]: So for example, you know, when we talk about cycle rickshaw pullers, the judgment that

00:14:55.200 --> 00:15:01.440
[Guest]: Delhi High Court passed, and it's stuck down some of the provisions that apply to cycle

00:15:01.440 --> 00:15:03.240
[Guest]: rickshaw pullers in Delhi.

00:15:03.240 --> 00:15:08.720
[Guest]: Those provisions were challenged four times in 80s before the Supreme Court and the Supreme

00:15:08.720 --> 00:15:11.000
[Guest]: Court upheld those provisions.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:16.320
[Guest]: And if you see those judgments, and if you see the rationale that the court gives, heavily

00:15:16.320 --> 00:15:23.440
[Guest]: influenced by socialist reasoning, and they mentioned this, and they call the entrepreneurs

00:15:23.440 --> 00:15:28.320
[Guest]: who own the cycle rickshaws, and so basically, let me first give you the background of what

00:15:28.320 --> 00:15:29.320
[Guest]: the law was about.

00:15:29.320 --> 00:15:34.360
[Guest]: There was another law which said that one person can't own more than one cycle rickshaw.

00:15:34.360 --> 00:15:39.800
[Guest]: So owner must be the puller, which meant that you can only own one cycle rickshaw, you will

00:15:39.800 --> 00:15:44.240
[Guest]: not give it on rent, but which also implied that no one else can hire a cycle rickshaw

00:15:44.240 --> 00:15:45.240
[Guest]: from the other person.

00:15:45.240 --> 00:15:50.000
[Guest]: Now, there were a lot of migrants who came from rural areas during the non-agriculture

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:57.600
[Guest]: season, and would come to cities and towns, and would hire cycle rickshaws, and would

00:15:57.600 --> 00:16:01.520
[Guest]: ply them and then probably after three, four months, will go back to villages.

00:16:01.520 --> 00:16:07.600
[Guest]: But when you prohibit, when you make it illegal to give it on rent or to hire cycle rickshaws,

00:16:07.600 --> 00:16:13.880
[Guest]: you are basically, by sort of intervention, you are attacking the economy, you are making

00:16:13.880 --> 00:16:16.480
[Guest]: that consensual transaction illegal.

00:16:16.480 --> 00:16:21.440
[Guest]: Their reasoning is that, you know, the person who owns more than one cycle rickshaw is a

00:16:21.440 --> 00:16:24.280
[Guest]: greedy capitalist, and they say that in their judgments.

00:16:24.280 --> 00:16:28.960
[Guest]: Now that judgment, those four judgments, look at the contrast between those four judgments

00:16:28.960 --> 00:16:35.000
[Guest]: and the Delhi High Court judgment where this time in 2010, the court calls the police,

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.520
[Guest]: you know, the harasser or the exploiter.

00:16:37.520 --> 00:16:42.720
[Guest]: So in 80s, the exploitation is done by so-called greedy capitalists.

00:16:42.720 --> 00:16:48.640
[Guest]: And in 2010, same issue, same problem, same law, and the court finds that it is the police

00:16:48.640 --> 00:16:52.560
[Amit Varma]: and the municipal officials who are exploiting the poor.

00:16:52.560 --> 00:16:54.620
[Amit Varma]: So let me sort of unpack this.

00:16:54.620 --> 00:16:59.840
[Amit Varma]: One is that to summarize what is wrong with that earlier socialist judgments of the 80s,

00:16:59.840 --> 00:17:05.200
[Amit Varma]: for example, just let's unpack that one clause that no one can own more than one cycle rickshaw.

00:17:05.200 --> 00:17:06.200
[Amit Varma]: What does it do?

00:17:06.200 --> 00:17:08.080
[Amit Varma]: Number one, it prohibits scale.

00:17:08.080 --> 00:17:11.600
[Amit Varma]: It means that if you get one cycle rickshaw and you're successful and you want to scale

00:17:11.600 --> 00:17:14.240
[Amit Varma]: up, you cannot do that, you're only allowed to own one.

00:17:14.240 --> 00:17:16.280
[Amit Varma]: Number two, it is an entry barrier.

00:17:16.280 --> 00:17:20.160
[Amit Varma]: If you want to be a cycle rickshaw puller, you have to then get the means to actually

00:17:20.160 --> 00:17:21.160
[Amit Varma]: own one.

00:17:21.160 --> 00:17:24.260
[Amit Varma]: It is illegal for you to drive one for somebody else.

00:17:24.260 --> 00:17:28.120
[Amit Varma]: And presumably, if you rent one against the law, then both you and the person you're renting

00:17:28.120 --> 00:17:32.200
[Amit Varma]: it from will have to pay bribes to the police concerned or whatever and do other jugaad

00:17:32.200 --> 00:17:33.400
[Amit Varma]: to get out of it.

00:17:33.400 --> 00:17:37.840
[Amit Varma]: The third aspect is that with restrictions like this, there is often the moralistic line

00:17:37.840 --> 00:17:42.640
[Amit Varma]: taken that, you know, it goes against a man's dignity to pull a cycle rickshaw.

00:17:42.640 --> 00:17:46.480
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, you know, for their own good, we should keep them away from it.

00:17:46.480 --> 00:17:51.560
[Amit Varma]: Where, again, what people fail to realize is that, yes, pulling a cycle rickshaw is

00:17:51.560 --> 00:17:54.460
[Amit Varma]: just an horrible job, you wouldn't wish it on anyone.

00:17:54.460 --> 00:17:58.920
[Amit Varma]: But everybody who is choosing to do so of his own free will, is doing so because it

00:17:58.920 --> 00:18:01.400
[Guest]: is the best option to him.

00:18:01.400 --> 00:18:07.080
[Amit Varma]: So you are actually condemning him to a life worse than that by taking away the best option

00:18:07.080 --> 00:18:09.560
[Amit Varma]: of employment open to him.

00:18:09.560 --> 00:18:12.240
[Amit Varma]: And it's kind of wrong for all these three reasons.

00:18:12.240 --> 00:18:17.240
[Amit Varma]: Another question that popped up when you were talking about the disparity between the 1980s

00:18:17.240 --> 00:18:22.100
[Amit Varma]: and the 2010 judgment, which you pointed out, which, you know, correctly, then shifts of

00:18:22.100 --> 00:18:26.680
[Amit Varma]: focus on police and municipal officials for their harassment.

00:18:26.680 --> 00:18:30.700
[Amit Varma]: Is that one is actually a two part question one, has it actually been a trend within the

00:18:30.700 --> 00:18:31.700
[Amit Varma]: judiciary?

00:18:31.700 --> 00:18:36.200
[Amit Varma]: Or is it an isolated instance of an opinion changing like this, from something less liberal

00:18:36.200 --> 00:18:38.320
[Amit Varma]: to more liberal, as we would call it?

00:18:38.320 --> 00:18:44.220
[Amit Varma]: And two, does the culture of a particular time determine the direction of court judgments

00:18:44.220 --> 00:18:51.140
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that do judges then feel a necessity to do a certain kind of posturing to get the

00:18:51.140 --> 00:18:56.720
[Amit Varma]: plaudits of their peers and, you know, their others in society?

00:18:56.720 --> 00:19:00.000
[Guest]: Well, that would require empirical research.

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:05.320
[Guest]: There is some empirical research, you know, what you're saying, Deirdre McCloskey has

00:19:05.320 --> 00:19:07.080
[Guest]: argued something similar.

00:19:07.080 --> 00:19:12.120
[Guest]: And Nimish Adia, who did his PhD under McCloskey.

00:19:12.120 --> 00:19:16.960
[Guest]: In his PhD thesis, he talks about something similar, you know, in the context of economic

00:19:16.960 --> 00:19:19.400
[Guest]: reforms India had in 1991.

00:19:19.400 --> 00:19:24.080
[Guest]: He says it was, you see the society changing.

00:19:24.080 --> 00:19:27.840
[Guest]: And he points out at the, you know, for example, the Bollywood movies.

00:19:27.840 --> 00:19:34.360
[Guest]: So you look at how capitalists were portrayed in the movies, in 50s, 60s, then suddenly

00:19:34.360 --> 00:19:37.440
[Guest]: in 70s, you see an angry young man.

00:19:37.440 --> 00:19:40.520
[Guest]: And the perception, the portrayal of the police also changes.

00:19:40.520 --> 00:19:44.000
[Guest]: And come 90s, and you see, you know, very benign capitalists.

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:49.960
[Guest]: So the movie Hum Aapke Hain Kaun was a story of a benign capitalist family.

00:19:49.960 --> 00:19:52.240
[Guest]: And then it changes.

00:19:52.240 --> 00:19:58.800
[Guest]: So I do believe that that plays a role and judges play to the gallery.

00:19:58.800 --> 00:19:59.800
[Amit Varma]: Fascinating.

00:19:59.800 --> 00:20:03.700
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of talk now about street vendors itself.

00:20:03.700 --> 00:20:08.480
[Amit Varma]: Can you sum up for me without kind of coming to present times and talking about the 2014

00:20:08.480 --> 00:20:13.280
[Amit Varma]: law and all that, and we'll come to that later, but sum up to me the problems that through

00:20:13.280 --> 00:20:17.240
[Amit Varma]: the decades, street vendors have typically faced.

00:20:17.240 --> 00:20:20.920
[Guest]: So let me begin the story from the 80s.

00:20:20.920 --> 00:20:25.000
[Guest]: You know, two cities, mainly Delhi and Mumbai had their largest share of cases on street

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:29.120
[Guest]: vending with before the Supreme Court.

00:20:29.120 --> 00:20:34.320
[Guest]: And there was a case from Mumbai in 1983, Bombay hawkers union, you know, the hawkers

00:20:34.320 --> 00:20:40.700
[Guest]: union actually challenged provisions of Bombay Municipal Corporation Act 1888.

00:20:40.700 --> 00:20:48.160
[Guest]: If you look at this act, the provisions of this act, these were very skeleton provisions.

00:20:48.160 --> 00:20:55.620
[Guest]: Okay, the provision did not have any details of how the commissioner will issue the licenses,

00:20:55.620 --> 00:21:00.760
[Guest]: it only talks about terms and condition and the commissioner can issue the licenses subject

00:21:00.760 --> 00:21:05.580
[Guest]: to those terms and condition, but it doesn't guide the commissioner as to what sort of

00:21:05.580 --> 00:21:10.180
[Guest]: parameters should he employ for giving licenses, what should be those terms and condition,

00:21:10.180 --> 00:21:12.080
[Guest]: nothing, no guidance.

00:21:12.080 --> 00:21:16.620
[Guest]: And this is cardinal principle of administrative law that when the parliament or you know,

00:21:16.620 --> 00:21:22.300
[Guest]: the legislature makes a law and delegate certain powers to the executive, there has to be some

00:21:22.300 --> 00:21:29.260
[Guest]: guidance given to the executive, because executive can't make law, the executive can make rules,

00:21:29.260 --> 00:21:33.300
[Guest]: but the rules are there just to fill the gaps, you know, just to fill the details, but the

00:21:33.300 --> 00:21:38.980
[Guest]: rules can't be abused or misused by the executive to do what as per its whims and fancies, that

00:21:38.980 --> 00:21:41.020
[Guest]: that's not permissible.

00:21:41.020 --> 00:21:46.940
[Guest]: And the court has the power of judicial review, that if there is over delegation, or if there

00:21:46.940 --> 00:21:50.860
[Guest]: is arbitrariness, then it can strike down those rules.

00:21:50.860 --> 00:21:56.420
[Guest]: So what this union was doing, the street vendors challenge those provisions saying that this

00:21:56.420 --> 00:22:02.660
[Guest]: is not guided discretion, it is unguided power in the hands of the executive, because they

00:22:02.660 --> 00:22:07.220
[Guest]: apply for licenses, and they don't get their license, they also don't get any response

00:22:07.220 --> 00:22:09.120
[Guest]: from the municipality.

00:22:09.120 --> 00:22:11.460
[Guest]: And there is no deadline to give any response.

00:22:11.460 --> 00:22:16.200
[Guest]: Now, this is purely an administrative law question, right?

00:22:16.200 --> 00:22:18.900
[Guest]: And something similar happened with Delhi vendors.

00:22:18.900 --> 00:22:23.020
[Guest]: So you know, there was a vendor in near Janpath called Sodhan Singh.

00:22:23.020 --> 00:22:26.580
[Guest]: And he faced the same issue, he was given a license.

00:22:26.580 --> 00:22:31.780
[Guest]: But when he applied for renewal of license, there was no reply.

00:22:31.780 --> 00:22:33.180
[Guest]: The license wasn't renewed.

00:22:33.180 --> 00:22:38.500
[Guest]: When he went to the Supreme Court, their NDMC filed an affidavit saying, well, we rejected

00:22:38.500 --> 00:22:44.620
[Guest]: his license on so and so reason that, you know, he is supposed to be a moving vendor,

00:22:44.620 --> 00:22:49.820
[Guest]: a mobile vendor, but he stands at the bus stop, you know, sort of like a stationary

00:22:49.820 --> 00:22:50.820
[Guest]: vendor.

00:22:50.820 --> 00:22:52.100
[Guest]: That's not permissible.

00:22:52.100 --> 00:22:55.580
[Guest]: And we allowed him to sell only peanuts.

00:22:55.580 --> 00:22:57.740
[Guest]: But he started selling garments.

00:22:57.740 --> 00:23:00.820
[Guest]: You know, I mean, is that a material fact?

00:23:00.820 --> 00:23:05.740
[Guest]: Why would you give license to just to sell one particular such specific commodity?

00:23:05.740 --> 00:23:10.220
[Guest]: And what is your interest to control what commodity will he sell?

00:23:10.220 --> 00:23:12.760
[Guest]: Of course, it's not selling bombs or ammunition.

00:23:12.760 --> 00:23:18.060
[Guest]: It's not very clear from the judgment whether the NDMC had informed him in some timeline

00:23:18.060 --> 00:23:23.340
[Guest]: in some deadline, you know, why they are rejecting his license.

00:23:23.340 --> 00:23:27.940
[Guest]: And so then he can if he disagrees with those reasons, he could have challenged that reasoning

00:23:27.940 --> 00:23:28.940
[Guest]: before the court.

00:23:28.940 --> 00:23:33.020
[Guest]: So that's not very clear whether he challenged that there was no reply from the NDMC or whether

00:23:33.020 --> 00:23:34.300
[Guest]: he challenged the reasons.

00:23:34.300 --> 00:23:39.180
[Guest]: I believe it was that he did not get any response and the NDMC filed his response only before

00:23:39.180 --> 00:23:40.180
[Guest]: the court later.

00:23:40.180 --> 00:23:44.860
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you've also given the example of Vishwanath Roy, who applied to who was a tea

00:23:44.860 --> 00:23:47.980
[Amit Varma]: seller who wanted to sell clothes instead.

00:23:47.980 --> 00:23:50.780
[Amit Varma]: And that went all the way to the Thareja committee.

00:23:50.780 --> 00:23:55.160
[Guest]: And then that went all the way from basically from NDMC to the Supreme Court.

00:23:55.160 --> 00:23:59.260
[Guest]: And that happened in 90s because there is a context to it that you know, while the Sodhan

00:23:59.260 --> 00:24:03.400
[Guest]: Singh and Bombay hawkers union judgments, you know, were being heard by the Supreme

00:24:03.400 --> 00:24:09.380
[Guest]: Court, the Supreme Court did not take up this judicial review question, the administrative

00:24:09.380 --> 00:24:10.720
[Guest]: law question.

00:24:10.720 --> 00:24:16.840
[Guest]: It abdicated from its role of doing the judicial review, and instead, it passed directions.

00:24:16.840 --> 00:24:21.260
[Guest]: So in case of Bombay hawkers union, it asked the commissioner to frame some details as

00:24:21.260 --> 00:24:23.140
[Guest]: to how it should give the licenses.

00:24:23.140 --> 00:24:27.700
[Guest]: Now, the commissioner did frame some directions, you know, which he called the scheme, and

00:24:27.700 --> 00:24:35.040
[Guest]: the court also sort of modified the scheme and passed an order with that modified scheme,

00:24:35.040 --> 00:24:39.900
[Guest]: but also asked the commissioner to take inputs from all stakeholders and further finalize

00:24:39.900 --> 00:24:40.900
[Guest]: the scheme.

00:24:40.900 --> 00:24:45.220
[Guest]: This was very, very ambiguous, not something which the court should have ideally done,

00:24:45.220 --> 00:24:50.940
[Guest]: because the court should have ideally scrutinized the provisions in the Municipal Corporation

00:24:50.940 --> 00:24:55.500
[Guest]: Act, whether there was unguided discretion, you know, whether there are parameters there

00:24:55.500 --> 00:24:56.660
[Guest]: or not.

00:24:56.660 --> 00:25:01.380
[Guest]: The scheme business was not, you know, something the court should have gotten into.

00:25:01.380 --> 00:25:04.300
[Guest]: And in case the municipal commissioner was framing a scheme, you know, he should have

00:25:04.300 --> 00:25:07.300
[Guest]: gone ahead and framed the scheme and notified it.

00:25:07.300 --> 00:25:10.620
[Guest]: And then the vendors could have challenged the scheme if they liked.

00:25:10.620 --> 00:25:13.100
[Guest]: But the court shouldn't have put the scheme in its order.

00:25:13.100 --> 00:25:16.500
[Guest]: Because once the court puts the scheme in its order, it seems the court has laid down

00:25:16.500 --> 00:25:21.660
[Guest]: the scheme, which still is, you know, the most courts, you'll see the subsequent judgments.

00:25:21.660 --> 00:25:25.260
[Guest]: And it seems that the court framed the scheme, and you can't touch the scheme now because

00:25:25.260 --> 00:25:28.320
[Guest]: it's court order and whatever the court says is law.

00:25:28.320 --> 00:25:32.620
[Guest]: And that's very problematic, because now that scheme is off judicial review.

00:25:32.620 --> 00:25:35.340
[Guest]: So who will review that scheme now?

00:25:35.340 --> 00:25:38.540
[Guest]: Subsequent judges won't touch it or this is laid down by the Supreme Court judges are

00:25:38.540 --> 00:25:41.420
[Guest]: seniors and that becomes problematic.

00:25:41.420 --> 00:25:50.460
[Guest]: In case of Delhi, NDMC, you know, told the court how this vendor has come to the Supreme

00:25:50.460 --> 00:25:54.780
[Guest]: Court under which law, you know, where is his right to come to the court?

00:25:54.780 --> 00:25:59.540
[Guest]: Is he saying that he has a right to sit on the road to vent?

00:25:59.540 --> 00:26:01.000
[Guest]: There is no such right.

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:05.620
[Guest]: So the vendor claimed that he has a fundamental right under Article 19, 1G, right to pursue

00:26:05.620 --> 00:26:08.420
[Guest]: any profession, business, trade, occupation.

00:26:08.420 --> 00:26:12.700
[Guest]: And NDMC said, well, you know, how can you have a fundamental right to sit squat on the

00:26:12.700 --> 00:26:13.700
[Guest]: road?

00:26:13.700 --> 00:26:15.660
[Guest]: There is no fundamental right like that.

00:26:15.660 --> 00:26:21.860
[Guest]: And the court, instead of again, reviewing the administrative law question and reviewing

00:26:21.860 --> 00:26:26.180
[Guest]: the municipal laws, got confused with this proposition.

00:26:26.180 --> 00:26:28.780
[Guest]: Is there a fundamental right or is there no fundamental right?

00:26:28.780 --> 00:26:32.620
[Guest]: Now, the problem is that there is conceptual ambiguity with the court.

00:26:32.620 --> 00:26:39.080
[Guest]: The court did not really understand that in our scheme of constitution, there is presumption

00:26:39.080 --> 00:26:41.140
[Guest]: of liberty.

00:26:41.140 --> 00:26:45.620
[Guest]: Citizens don't have to ask and take permissions before they do something.

00:26:45.620 --> 00:26:46.980
[Amit Varma]: Liberty is not granted to us.

00:26:46.980 --> 00:26:51.380
[Amit Varma]: It is assumed and the burden of proof and argument is on someone who wishes to take

00:26:51.380 --> 00:26:52.380
[Amit Varma]: it away.

00:26:52.380 --> 00:26:53.380
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:26:53.380 --> 00:26:54.380
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:26:54.380 --> 00:26:55.380
[Guest]: Right.

00:26:55.380 --> 00:26:59.740
[Guest]: So we live in a system where the government, where the parliament, not the government,

00:26:59.740 --> 00:27:04.620
[Guest]: where the parliament or the legislature can restrict our rights because there is a system

00:27:04.620 --> 00:27:05.620
[Guest]: of restriction.

00:27:05.620 --> 00:27:08.420
[Guest]: So first of all, number one, constitution doesn't give us rights.

00:27:08.420 --> 00:27:11.980
[Guest]: The constitution declares that we have rights.

00:27:11.980 --> 00:27:12.980
[Guest]: That's number one.

00:27:12.980 --> 00:27:19.180
[Guest]: Number two, it gives the power to the legislature to restrict those rights reasonably and in

00:27:19.180 --> 00:27:22.380
[Guest]: general public interest for the purpose of 19, 1G.

00:27:22.380 --> 00:27:26.100
[Guest]: So you have two grounds, a there should be reasonableness and second is general public

00:27:26.100 --> 00:27:27.100
[Guest]: interest.

00:27:27.100 --> 00:27:28.100
[Guest]: Right.

00:27:28.100 --> 00:27:34.140
[Guest]: And then a citizen can challenge those restrictions on the ground that either it is not reasonable

00:27:34.140 --> 00:27:36.420
[Guest]: or it is not in general public interest.

00:27:36.420 --> 00:27:39.800
[Guest]: This is precisely that the vendors were doing.

00:27:39.800 --> 00:27:44.180
[Guest]: They were saying, of course, on the administrative law grounds that, you know, this is not a

00:27:44.180 --> 00:27:47.540
[Guest]: law because it goes beyond the law.

00:27:47.540 --> 00:27:52.260
[Guest]: The law doesn't ask you to, you know, and you have to have some procedural safeguards

00:27:52.260 --> 00:27:55.220
[Guest]: on the issue of procedure, also the challenge, but they could have also challenged it on

00:27:55.220 --> 00:27:57.620
[Guest]: reasonableness and general public interest.

00:27:57.620 --> 00:28:02.860
[Guest]: The court, instead of asking that question, got into the question, where is the right?

00:28:02.860 --> 00:28:05.360
[Guest]: And this is really, really troubling.

00:28:05.360 --> 00:28:08.860
[Guest]: The court doesn't understand, you know, the way the right is coming from.

00:28:08.860 --> 00:28:11.340
[Guest]: And these are the Supreme Court judges.

00:28:11.340 --> 00:28:14.100
[Guest]: And this is really dangerous for the society.

00:28:14.100 --> 00:28:18.940
[Guest]: I mean, if the Supreme Court judges are not very clear, you know, where the source of

00:28:18.940 --> 00:28:23.180
[Guest]: the right or the concept of fundamental rights, then God save the country and the presumption

00:28:23.180 --> 00:28:25.580
[Guest]: of liberty and the presumption of liberty.

00:28:25.580 --> 00:28:27.300
[Guest]: So I'll give you another example.

00:28:27.300 --> 00:28:30.020
[Guest]: So for example, you know, drone was a recent phenomenon.

00:28:30.020 --> 00:28:34.380
[Guest]: There were no drones earlier, or for example, e-rickshaws, you know, the battery operated

00:28:34.380 --> 00:28:38.820
[Guest]: rickshaws, battery operated rickshaws didn't come under the purview of Motor Vehicles Act,

00:28:38.820 --> 00:28:41.420
[Guest]: but they were not cycle rickshaws either, right?

00:28:41.420 --> 00:28:45.240
[Guest]: But the government did not have a law to ban them.

00:28:45.240 --> 00:28:50.620
[Guest]: So the question is, is it legal to ply battery operated rickshaws or not?

00:28:50.620 --> 00:28:55.100
[Guest]: I argue, yes, it is legal, because you don't have any law to ban them, or for that matter,

00:28:55.100 --> 00:28:56.100
[Guest]: cryptocurrency.

00:28:56.100 --> 00:28:57.940
[Guest]: Where is your law to ban cryptocurrency?

00:28:57.940 --> 00:29:01.580
[Guest]: Cryptocurrency is a commodity, and you can trade in cryptocurrency.

00:29:01.580 --> 00:29:07.020
[Guest]: But the government has gone ahead to ban cryptocurrency by way of a notification, which is not even

00:29:07.020 --> 00:29:08.020
[Guest]: a law.

00:29:08.020 --> 00:29:09.620
[Amit Varma]: It's not passed by Parliament yet.

00:29:09.620 --> 00:29:14.380
[Amit Varma]: So what you're saying is, if cryptocurrency has to be banned, then Parliament has to pass

00:29:14.380 --> 00:29:20.100
[Amit Varma]: a law that is either on the grounds of reasonableness, reasonable restrictions, or public order.

00:29:20.100 --> 00:29:23.600
[Amit Varma]: Both reasonableness and public and general public interest.

00:29:23.600 --> 00:29:29.340
[Amit Varma]: And then those who are affected can go to the court and argue about that.

00:29:29.340 --> 00:29:33.580
[Amit Varma]: But it is not for the executive to, you know, without the legislature having passed such

00:29:33.580 --> 00:29:39.020
[Amit Varma]: a law to frame a rule that is effectively a law and they can't do that is unconstitutional.

00:29:39.020 --> 00:29:40.020
[Guest]: You're arguing.

00:29:40.020 --> 00:29:41.020
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:29:41.020 --> 00:29:43.380
[Amit Varma]: Two questions come up here.

00:29:43.380 --> 00:29:47.160
[Amit Varma]: One is that one of the themes through all your work, like I've read your papers and

00:29:47.160 --> 00:29:48.300
[Amit Varma]: your articles and all of that.

00:29:48.300 --> 00:29:53.420
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things I find in the facts that you lay out before us is that there seems

00:29:53.420 --> 00:29:59.500
[Amit Varma]: to be a tremendous flouting of this whole notion of the separation of powers, that the

00:29:59.500 --> 00:30:04.060
[Amit Varma]: judiciary should do this, the legislature should do this, the executive should do this.

00:30:04.060 --> 00:30:09.060
[Amit Varma]: An example being in that superb sentence that you said earlier in this episode about the

00:30:09.060 --> 00:30:15.860
[Amit Varma]: Supreme Court directing the government to pass a federal law about a municipal issue.

00:30:15.860 --> 00:30:18.100
[Amit Varma]: And this seems completely confused.

00:30:18.100 --> 00:30:24.980
[Amit Varma]: So does this confusion at the level of conception where, you know, the Supreme Court is legislating

00:30:24.980 --> 00:30:30.180
[Amit Varma]: from the bench and the legislator is pretty toothless these days, but and the executive

00:30:30.180 --> 00:30:35.660
[Amit Varma]: is doing what the legislature should do and the center is passing laws for municipalities,

00:30:35.660 --> 00:30:40.700
[Amit Varma]: you know, is this just a fundamental problem in any change getting done even outside of

00:30:40.700 --> 00:30:43.340
[Amit Varma]: this limited context that we're talking about today?

00:30:43.340 --> 00:30:48.180
[Guest]: So you know, also, let's complete our chain of events, because after they passed directions

00:30:48.180 --> 00:30:54.820
[Guest]: in Bombay Hawkers Union, in case of Delhi also, what they did in Delhi, Delhi was even

00:30:54.820 --> 00:31:01.140
[Guest]: more weirder, because they constituted a five judge bench to decide whether it's a constitutional,

00:31:01.140 --> 00:31:03.180
[Guest]: it's a fundamental right or not.

00:31:03.180 --> 00:31:07.780
[Guest]: And it decided that it is a fundamental right and the parliament can restrict it.

00:31:07.780 --> 00:31:12.460
[Guest]: And they said now the individual or the smaller benches will decide on the individual cases,

00:31:12.460 --> 00:31:18.160
[Guest]: because Sodhan Singh was not an isolated case, they were, it was a bunch of cases.

00:31:18.160 --> 00:31:24.540
[Guest]: But what seems in the later subsequent judgments, I found the reference to, you know, what happened

00:31:24.540 --> 00:31:29.020
[Guest]: to the rest of cases is that they forwarded those cases to a Lok Adalat.

00:31:29.020 --> 00:31:34.820
[Guest]: Now this is bizarre, because Article 32 of our Constitution guarantees that the Supreme

00:31:34.820 --> 00:31:37.020
[Guest]: Court is bound to hear your writ petitions.

00:31:37.020 --> 00:31:42.020
[Guest]: Writ petition meaning if you challenge, you know, a government action or a state law that

00:31:42.020 --> 00:31:46.020
[Guest]: it violates your fundamental rights, the Supreme Court is bound to hear.

00:31:46.020 --> 00:31:47.020
[Guest]: It's a guarantee.

00:31:47.020 --> 00:31:48.380
[Guest]: It's a constitutional guarantee.

00:31:48.380 --> 00:31:53.900
[Guest]: And the Supreme Court forwarding these writ petitions to a Lok Adalat, I think that's

00:31:53.900 --> 00:31:59.140
[Guest]: absolutely bizarre and there is no other parallel or there is no other example to my mind.

00:31:59.140 --> 00:32:04.300
[Guest]: I mean, imagine, you know, people would be on streets and the Supreme Court forwarded,

00:32:04.300 --> 00:32:08.260
[Guest]: let's say the Kashmir issue or the Ram Mandir issue or the, you know, something of that

00:32:08.260 --> 00:32:09.940
[Guest]: sort to Lok Adalat.

00:32:09.940 --> 00:32:13.420
[Guest]: And but this is what exactly they did in 1990.

00:32:13.420 --> 00:32:16.380
[Guest]: And after that, they started constituting committees.

00:32:16.380 --> 00:32:18.460
[Guest]: So first they constitute a Thareja committee.

00:32:18.460 --> 00:32:24.620
[Guest]: So they took up a civil judge from the lower judiciary in Delhi and asked him to, you know,

00:32:24.620 --> 00:32:27.860
[Guest]: basically, it was a committee of one person.

00:32:27.860 --> 00:32:31.380
[Guest]: And he was on the streets of Delhi, you know, counting vendors.

00:32:31.380 --> 00:32:35.500
[Guest]: And but why are you counting vendors?

00:32:35.500 --> 00:32:37.820
[Guest]: You know, why are you counting vendors?

00:32:37.820 --> 00:32:44.940
[Guest]: Now, the other problem is, the court forgets that street vending is not the only private

00:32:44.940 --> 00:32:46.980
[Guest]: use of public space.

00:32:46.980 --> 00:32:50.140
[Guest]: There are many other private uses of public space.

00:32:50.140 --> 00:32:55.000
[Guest]: So for example, car parking, you know, we are recording here in this neighborhood.

00:32:55.000 --> 00:32:56.940
[Guest]: This is a residential zone.

00:32:56.940 --> 00:33:00.940
[Guest]: And you see cars there on the road on the pavement.

00:33:00.940 --> 00:33:04.940
[Guest]: Are these people paying to the municipality for parking their cars on the pavement?

00:33:04.940 --> 00:33:06.340
[Guest]: No one is paying.

00:33:06.340 --> 00:33:08.660
[Guest]: Is it legal or illegal?

00:33:08.660 --> 00:33:12.620
[Guest]: You ask this question to municipal official, he won't also know, right?

00:33:12.620 --> 00:33:16.420
[Guest]: So the cars are being parked in a public space without payment.

00:33:16.420 --> 00:33:17.940
[Guest]: Is it legal or illegal?

00:33:17.940 --> 00:33:19.640
[Guest]: No one comes to take off the cars.

00:33:19.640 --> 00:33:23.900
[Guest]: In commercial districts, yes, that happens that sometimes the crane comes or the traffic

00:33:23.900 --> 00:33:28.740
[Guest]: guy comes to chalan you, but that doesn't happen in the residential zone.

00:33:28.740 --> 00:33:34.260
[Guest]: So other use, for example, the building repairing, you know, the building owner would put a scaffolding

00:33:34.260 --> 00:33:38.620
[Guest]: and the scaffolding often is in the public area, right?

00:33:38.620 --> 00:33:43.580
[Guest]: You have building materials lying outside in the public area, or let's say family picnic

00:33:43.580 --> 00:33:45.860
[Guest]: in a public park, right?

00:33:45.860 --> 00:33:51.260
[Guest]: Why people smoking outside on the road and blocking the pedestrian path, isn't that a

00:33:51.260 --> 00:33:52.380
[Guest]: public use?

00:33:52.380 --> 00:33:57.220
[Guest]: And for that matter, you know, we are in Delhi, barats, barat is the biggest example, you

00:33:57.220 --> 00:34:00.780
[Guest]: don't take any public permission, the police permission or the traffic permission, you

00:34:00.780 --> 00:34:05.140
[Guest]: know, to have a barat on the roads and the roads are jammed when there is, you know,

00:34:05.140 --> 00:34:09.500
[Guest]: we call it in Delhi, sayabhari hai, there are a lot of marriages, weddings happening

00:34:09.500 --> 00:34:15.840
[Guest]: on a particular night because of a shubh muhurat and the roads are jammed because of barats.

00:34:15.840 --> 00:34:21.700
[Guest]: But no one raises any questions on these other public uses.

00:34:21.700 --> 00:34:24.700
[Guest]: It's only the street vendor issue where there are a lot of questions.

00:34:24.700 --> 00:34:29.860
[Guest]: So my question is, to the Supreme Court that while you frame a committee, he's counting

00:34:29.860 --> 00:34:32.580
[Guest]: vendors on the road, but what about other public uses?

00:34:32.580 --> 00:34:36.220
[Guest]: And while they were thinking, and of course, the one problem is that they were trying to

00:34:36.220 --> 00:34:38.260
[Guest]: regulate street vending.

00:34:38.260 --> 00:34:41.820
[Guest]: But the other problem is, which they shouldn't have done.

00:34:41.820 --> 00:34:49.100
[Guest]: But the other problem is while doing that, they left other private uses of public spaces.

00:34:49.100 --> 00:34:53.700
[Guest]: I mean, they left those unregulated, they didn't think about that.

00:34:53.700 --> 00:34:55.340
[Amit Varma]: And this is also a philosophical question.

00:34:55.340 --> 00:35:00.500
[Amit Varma]: And while you pointed out that the Supreme Court went into the wrong direction by considering

00:35:00.500 --> 00:35:05.900
[Amit Varma]: whether this fundamental right exists at all, it seemed to have actually then at least come

00:35:05.900 --> 00:35:09.560
[Amit Varma]: to the correct conclusion that yes, a fundamental right exists.

00:35:09.560 --> 00:35:14.100
[Amit Varma]: And as you've pointed out that the government does not own the roads, the people on the

00:35:14.100 --> 00:35:18.540
[Amit Varma]: roads, and the government is merely a trustee of the roads, right.

00:35:18.540 --> 00:35:24.420
[Guest]: So this was also in one of those, as it said, no 50 and 60 judges gave much better judgments.

00:35:24.420 --> 00:35:27.620
[Guest]: And this was in 55 and 57.

00:35:27.620 --> 00:35:32.420
[Guest]: There were a couple of judgments where the court pointed out that the judgments, the

00:35:32.420 --> 00:35:36.180
[Guest]: municipal or any government is not the owner of the roads, they are merely trustees of

00:35:36.180 --> 00:35:37.180
[Guest]: the road.

00:35:37.180 --> 00:35:40.080
[Guest]: So they can make regulations for better coordination.

00:35:40.080 --> 00:35:44.380
[Guest]: But they can't oust people from walking on the road, or from applying their vehicles

00:35:44.380 --> 00:35:46.220
[Guest]: on the road, and so on and so forth.

00:35:46.220 --> 00:35:47.220
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:35:47.220 --> 00:35:50.500
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, the question that automatically comes up, takes me to something that the Bombay

00:35:50.500 --> 00:35:55.900
[Amit Varma]: High Court in 2014 said, which you've quoted in one of your pieces, which both plays to

00:35:55.900 --> 00:36:02.740
[Amit Varma]: this question and also sort of seems to articulate the common impression that most people have

00:36:02.740 --> 00:36:04.420
[Amit Varma]: about street hawkers.

00:36:04.420 --> 00:36:09.780
[Amit Varma]: And the court is, quote, street hawkers create dirt and nuisance, if they were to be conceded

00:36:09.780 --> 00:36:15.700
[Amit Varma]: the right claim by them, they could hold society to ransom by squatting.

00:36:15.700 --> 00:36:21.100
[Amit Varma]: And you know, in 2017, you've pointed out how the Delhi High Court said, quote, being

00:36:21.100 --> 00:36:24.780
[Amit Varma]: pitched between the conflicting rights of the livelihood of street vendors versus the

00:36:24.780 --> 00:36:28.860
[Amit Varma]: life and security of the public in general, including the street vendors, we are of the

00:36:28.860 --> 00:36:33.560
[Amit Varma]: opinion that the former must bow to the latter as without life and security, no question

00:36:33.560 --> 00:36:36.420
[Amit Varma]: of earning a livelihood can arise, stop quote.

00:36:36.420 --> 00:36:41.060
[Amit Varma]: So now, you know, just at the level of the fundamental principles involved, we would

00:36:41.060 --> 00:36:45.420
[Amit Varma]: both agree with the judgment you cited from the 50s that, you know, public space belongs

00:36:45.420 --> 00:36:49.900
[Amit Varma]: to the public, not to the government, the government is sort of safeguarding those spaces.

00:36:49.900 --> 00:36:53.260
[Amit Varma]: So equally, you know, people have a right to sell things, people have a right to walk

00:36:53.260 --> 00:36:57.260
[Amit Varma]: on those streets, we can stand together and you know, have a smoke break or whatever the

00:36:57.260 --> 00:37:01.520
[Amit Varma]: why don't smoke and you know, the people can park their things there and whatever.

00:37:01.520 --> 00:37:06.460
[Amit Varma]: The question that arises here is, and I'm kind of thinking aloud, is that if you're

00:37:06.460 --> 00:37:12.140
[Amit Varma]: to take a thought experiment, where would you draw a line, because the more people sort

00:37:12.140 --> 00:37:19.020
[Amit Varma]: of use these public spaces, each use has a tiny disruption that does not justify or is

00:37:19.020 --> 00:37:23.700
[Amit Varma]: not a reasonable restriction of that right, to what point where where do you draw the

00:37:23.700 --> 00:37:28.660
[Amit Varma]: line where the disruptions get so much that you say that no more this is not allowed.

00:37:28.660 --> 00:37:33.140
[Amit Varma]: For example, if we were to take a crowd of people and completely block a public street

00:37:33.140 --> 00:37:37.420
[Amit Varma]: outside here in Housecast where we are recording for days on end, the government would have

00:37:37.420 --> 00:37:40.460
[Amit Varma]: to intervene because we'd be blocking all the highways and it would affect traffic all

00:37:40.460 --> 00:37:41.700
[Amit Varma]: over the city.

00:37:41.700 --> 00:37:45.080
[Amit Varma]: But when that happens for shorter periods of time, like say the Ganpati Emotions in

00:37:45.080 --> 00:37:48.820
[Amit Varma]: Bombay where I live, the government doesn't do anything because it's just a handful of

00:37:48.820 --> 00:37:51.140
[Amit Varma]: days and whatever let it happen.

00:37:51.140 --> 00:37:54.700
[Amit Varma]: You know, one, where is the line to on what basis do you think the line should be drawn

00:37:54.700 --> 00:38:00.220
[Amit Varma]: and is that necessarily an arbitrary distinction and three, would you agree that the street

00:38:00.220 --> 00:38:04.460
[Amit Varma]: hawkers no matter you know, in the current dispensation, no matter what they do, simply

00:38:04.460 --> 00:38:08.260
[Amit Varma]: do not come anywhere close to that line, they are not disrupting life in that manner.

00:38:08.260 --> 00:38:13.780
[Guest]: I'm seeing the line can be anywhere, but it has to be a general line, a general line for

00:38:13.780 --> 00:38:14.980
[Guest]: everyone.

00:38:14.980 --> 00:38:23.940
[Guest]: It has to be same line for car owners, for, you know, baratis, for street vendors, for

00:38:23.940 --> 00:38:27.180
[Guest]: cars that ply on the road, because that's also, you know, the roads are also public

00:38:27.180 --> 00:38:30.820
[Guest]: spaces for building repairs or building construction works.

00:38:30.820 --> 00:38:36.220
[Guest]: So it has to be general guidelines for all sort of private uses of public space, but

00:38:36.220 --> 00:38:42.500
[Guest]: you can't say that for a particular private use, that this is the nuisance created creating

00:38:42.500 --> 00:38:51.140
[Guest]: use and on what basis and there it, you know, smells of some sort of bias, elite bias against

00:38:51.140 --> 00:38:56.260
[Amit Varma]: sport, there's a clear class bias here, because I, you know, I can park my fancy SUV on the

00:38:56.260 --> 00:38:57.580
[Guest]: road all day.

00:38:57.580 --> 00:39:01.620
[Amit Varma]: And nobody will really dare to mess with me, though, I must point out, I don't have a fancy

00:39:01.620 --> 00:39:02.620
[Amit Varma]: SUV.

00:39:02.620 --> 00:39:03.740
[Amit Varma]: This is purely hypothetical.

00:39:03.740 --> 00:39:06.220
[Amit Varma]: But I could park my fancy SUV on the road all day.

00:39:06.220 --> 00:39:09.980
[Amit Varma]: And a street vendor occupying less space than that will constantly be harassed.

00:39:09.980 --> 00:39:14.100
[Amit Varma]: And as you pointed out, we'll have to pay rent to three sources to the police, the municipal

00:39:14.100 --> 00:39:20.020
[Amit Varma]: authorities, and to the shopkeeper in front of who shop he might be, even though the shopkeeper

00:39:20.020 --> 00:39:21.300
[Amit Varma]: doesn't own that space.

00:39:21.300 --> 00:39:22.300
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:39:22.300 --> 00:39:28.100
[Guest]: So, you know, it's basically a Coasean arrangement between the shopkeeper and the street vendor.

00:39:28.100 --> 00:39:32.740
[Guest]: So the street vendor tries to buy his new objection, so that he doesn't complain to

00:39:32.740 --> 00:39:35.140
[Guest]: the police and allows him to stand there.

00:39:35.140 --> 00:39:39.940
[Guest]: Although the street, the shopkeeper doesn't own that space to the municipal officials

00:39:39.940 --> 00:39:45.020
[Guest]: so that they don't take action against him and to the police again for no harassment.

00:39:45.020 --> 00:39:50.300
[Guest]: But still, you know, maybe someone else, let's say RWAs, Resident Welfare Associations, who

00:39:50.300 --> 00:39:54.620
[Guest]: are very active and powerful these days, they can complain against the vendors and despite

00:39:54.620 --> 00:39:58.540
[Guest]: all his bribery and whatever, he can still be removed.

00:39:58.540 --> 00:40:02.820
[Guest]: So there is still no certainty and assurance despite the bribe given.

00:40:02.820 --> 00:40:06.860
[Amit Varma]: And the other thing that also strikes me is, you correctly pointed out earlier, that there

00:40:06.860 --> 00:40:10.300
[Amit Varma]: are all these different kinds of private uses of public spaces.

00:40:10.300 --> 00:40:15.260
[Amit Varma]: Now, if I were to give a hierarchy to them, I would actually give more importance and

00:40:15.260 --> 00:40:19.020
[Amit Varma]: more freedom to the street vendor than to the SUV parker.

00:40:19.020 --> 00:40:23.220
[Amit Varma]: Because the street vendor is there because he is performing a social need.

00:40:23.220 --> 00:40:25.780
[Amit Varma]: He is only there because people want to buy from him.

00:40:25.780 --> 00:40:27.260
[Amit Varma]: All transactions are positive.

00:40:27.260 --> 00:40:29.260
[Amit Varma]: Some games are mutually beneficial.

00:40:29.260 --> 00:40:31.080
[Amit Varma]: So you know, that's the logic of the market.

00:40:31.080 --> 00:40:36.260
[Amit Varma]: He exists because he fulfills a social need, sort of a public utility, a public utility.

00:40:36.260 --> 00:40:40.340
[Amit Varma]: The guy who parks his SUV is not fulfilling anyone's need, but his own.

00:40:40.340 --> 00:40:41.340
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

00:40:41.340 --> 00:40:44.900
[Amit Varma]: You know, so what were the sort of battles that you guys were fighting, you know, on

00:40:44.900 --> 00:40:49.600
[Amit Varma]: behalf of the street vendors of Delhi and Jaipur, where I guess your local energies

00:40:49.600 --> 00:40:50.860
[Amit Varma]: were restricted?

00:40:50.860 --> 00:40:55.140
[Amit Varma]: What were typically the, you know, at a micro level, the problems that would be faced?

00:40:55.140 --> 00:40:59.260
[Amit Varma]: Like, I guess one problem is just a problem of existence, where because you're illegal,

00:40:59.260 --> 00:41:01.540
[Amit Varma]: you have to pay bribes to all of these people.

00:41:01.540 --> 00:41:05.580
[Amit Varma]: So at what different levels were you trying to bring about changes to this?

00:41:05.580 --> 00:41:11.700
[Guest]: So you know, in 2014, the law was passed, associations, vendors were very happy.

00:41:11.700 --> 00:41:15.820
[Guest]: There was one provision in the law which said that unless there is a survey done, all the

00:41:15.820 --> 00:41:17.500
[Guest]: vendors are counted.

00:41:17.500 --> 00:41:20.300
[Guest]: No vendor can be evicted until then.

00:41:20.300 --> 00:41:24.420
[Guest]: And this was a very strong provision because the way it was worded, you know, no vendor

00:41:24.420 --> 00:41:26.000
[Guest]: shall be evicted.

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:29.420
[Guest]: There was a very clear direct mandate that you just can't evict any vendors.

00:41:29.420 --> 00:41:33.580
[Amit Varma]: So just to clarify, what this means is that the government then has to mandatorily carry

00:41:33.580 --> 00:41:39.380
[Guest]: out a survey of existing street vendors, and it cannot evict any of them once that is done.

00:41:39.380 --> 00:41:40.380
[Guest]: Until that is done.

00:41:40.380 --> 00:41:41.380
[Amit Varma]: Until that is done.

00:41:41.380 --> 00:41:42.900
[Guest]: Until that is done.

00:41:42.900 --> 00:41:48.900
[Guest]: And but we got some news from Jaipur that evictions were still being carried on by the

00:41:48.900 --> 00:41:50.500
[Guest]: municipality.

00:41:50.500 --> 00:41:54.280
[Guest]: And we decided to visit Jaipur in January 2015.

00:41:54.280 --> 00:41:55.540
[Guest]: We met the vendors.

00:41:55.540 --> 00:42:01.500
[Guest]: And suddenly we got the news from a vendor that, you know, the municipality was carrying

00:42:01.500 --> 00:42:03.260
[Guest]: on eviction somewhere.

00:42:03.260 --> 00:42:06.620
[Guest]: And we reached that spot and they were bulldozers because, you know, in Jaipur, they call it

00:42:06.620 --> 00:42:07.940
[Guest]: thadis.

00:42:07.940 --> 00:42:14.420
[Guest]: So they have some sort of platform built roadside where they sell their wares and things like

00:42:14.420 --> 00:42:15.420
[Guest]: that.

00:42:15.420 --> 00:42:16.420
[Guest]: So they were bulldozers.

00:42:16.420 --> 00:42:21.060
[Guest]: They were heavy deployment of police forces and a lot of municipal officials were there.

00:42:21.060 --> 00:42:29.180
[Guest]: And we saw those thadis being bulldozed, although there was a, you know, state run dairy kiosk

00:42:29.180 --> 00:42:30.180
[Guest]: that was left.

00:42:30.180 --> 00:42:34.780
[Guest]: They didn't do anything to that state dairy kiosk.

00:42:34.780 --> 00:42:38.940
[Guest]: We went to a police station because as per the law, this was illegal.

00:42:38.940 --> 00:42:41.860
[Guest]: And I asked them to lodge an FIR and they laughed at us.

00:42:41.860 --> 00:42:42.860
[Guest]: They said, under what law?

00:42:42.860 --> 00:42:43.900
[Guest]: I said, this is the law.

00:42:43.900 --> 00:42:44.900
[Guest]: They didn't know about the law.

00:42:44.900 --> 00:42:47.700
[Guest]: They said, yeh kaunsa kanun hai, humein nahi pata.

00:42:47.700 --> 00:42:52.740
[Guest]: I said, aap kahaan par hai, Rajasthan, Rajasthan Hindustan mein aata hai ya Pakistan mein aata

00:42:52.740 --> 00:42:53.740
[Guest]: hai.

00:42:53.740 --> 00:43:01.500
[Guest]: So parliament passing a law and the police doesn't respect, doesn't care about that law.

00:43:01.500 --> 00:43:04.700
[Guest]: We decided to then approach the Rajasthan High Court.

00:43:04.700 --> 00:43:11.940
[Guest]: We filed a writ and lo and behold, the Rajasthan High Court decides that the law is not applicable

00:43:11.940 --> 00:43:13.500
[Guest]: to state of Rajasthan.

00:43:13.500 --> 00:43:15.500
[Amit Varma]: My God, on what basis do they make that?

00:43:15.500 --> 00:43:16.940
[Guest]: They say it's not notified yet.

00:43:16.940 --> 00:43:19.260
[Guest]: They say they acknowledge that there is a law.

00:43:19.260 --> 00:43:21.860
[Guest]: They say Rajasthan government hasn't notified.

00:43:21.860 --> 00:43:25.940
[Guest]: But the thing they missed is that the central government had notified it for the whole of

00:43:25.940 --> 00:43:29.040
[Guest]: India and it was notified.

00:43:29.040 --> 00:43:34.500
[Guest]: Then we got hold of a Rajya Sabha MP from Rajasthan and requested him to raise this

00:43:34.500 --> 00:43:35.500
[Guest]: question in the parliament.

00:43:35.500 --> 00:43:40.260
[Guest]: And of course, the minister, concerned minister replied that it is indeed applicable to whole

00:43:40.260 --> 00:43:43.100
[Guest]: of India and the notification was in public domain.

00:43:43.100 --> 00:43:47.700
[Guest]: So we took both, you know, the notification and his reply to the Supreme Court.

00:43:47.700 --> 00:43:49.180
[Guest]: We filed a case there.

00:43:49.180 --> 00:43:52.740
[Guest]: Ideally, the case should have been decided on the first hearing because there is nothing

00:43:52.740 --> 00:43:54.780
[Guest]: much to be decided.

00:43:54.780 --> 00:44:00.020
[Guest]: Yet this court took one year and after six or eight months, I think it was quite evident

00:44:00.020 --> 00:44:04.300
[Guest]: to the state of Rajasthan and to the municipal corporation there that they will have to implement

00:44:04.300 --> 00:44:05.300
[Guest]: the law.

00:44:05.300 --> 00:44:07.340
[Guest]: There is, you know, no other escape.

00:44:07.340 --> 00:44:09.100
[Guest]: So they drafted the rules and the scheme.

00:44:09.100 --> 00:44:13.180
[Guest]: I'm not too sure if they notified it, but they probably put the draft in the public

00:44:13.180 --> 00:44:18.660
[Guest]: domain and after vacations, the court heard the matter and they say, well, the matter

00:44:18.660 --> 00:44:27.220
[Guest]: is now, you know, sort of, because what you were asking for, they have sort of done that.

00:44:27.220 --> 00:44:28.220
[Amit Varma]: So it's moot now.

00:44:28.220 --> 00:44:29.220
[Guest]: So it's moot now.

00:44:29.220 --> 00:44:30.900
[Guest]: There is no point deciding in the matter.

00:44:30.900 --> 00:44:36.580
[Guest]: What they did in their order is to record the statement of the government lawyer and

00:44:36.580 --> 00:44:41.040
[Guest]: also my statement and they say that on these terms, we dispose of the matter.

00:44:41.040 --> 00:44:45.700
[Guest]: But they did not expressly overrule the high court judgment, unfortunately, which ideally

00:44:45.700 --> 00:44:48.780
[Guest]: they should have done, but they didn't do that.

00:44:48.780 --> 00:44:51.060
[Guest]: Anyways, the state of Rajasthan implemented the law.

00:44:51.060 --> 00:44:53.420
[Guest]: That was one victory.

00:44:53.420 --> 00:45:00.980
[Guest]: Then I thought, you know, one state, we spent one year pushing that state to implement the

00:45:00.980 --> 00:45:04.380
[Guest]: law or just frame like rules and scheme.

00:45:04.380 --> 00:45:06.060
[Guest]: How do we deal with all the states?

00:45:06.060 --> 00:45:12.060
[Guest]: And that's how we came up with the idea to design an index, which would be an interstate

00:45:12.060 --> 00:45:17.020
[Guest]: index that shows which state has to what extent implemented the law.

00:45:17.020 --> 00:45:22.580
[Guest]: And in 2017, we, you know, launched the first version of the index, then last year, we did

00:45:22.580 --> 00:45:28.660
[Guest]: the second version, which shows that, you know, the implementation is really poor.

00:45:28.660 --> 00:45:32.420
[Guest]: And most states have not implemented at best they might have.

00:45:32.420 --> 00:45:37.060
[Guest]: So barring three or four states, most states have drafted their rules and schemes.

00:45:37.060 --> 00:45:42.820
[Guest]: But in terms of constituting town vending committee, which is a participatory forum,

00:45:42.820 --> 00:45:47.980
[Guest]: also comprising of the street vendors, almost one third have only one third towns and cities

00:45:47.980 --> 00:45:52.380
[Guest]: have constituted town vending committees, but almost two third have not done that.

00:45:52.380 --> 00:45:53.380
[Guest]: And then there are other steps.

00:45:53.380 --> 00:45:56.460
[Guest]: So, for example, there should be a grievance redressal forum and so on and so forth, which

00:45:56.460 --> 00:46:00.140
[Guest]: most cities or municipalities have not done.

00:46:00.140 --> 00:46:03.740
[Guest]: So the law is barely implemented, right.

00:46:03.740 --> 00:46:07.620
[Amit Varma]: So you know, before we go into a break, I'll quickly read out the three features of the

00:46:07.620 --> 00:46:10.500
[Amit Varma]: 2014 act that you point out.

00:46:10.500 --> 00:46:15.500
[Amit Varma]: So they can then form the basis of discussion when we return to figure out how you the impact

00:46:15.500 --> 00:46:19.140
[Amit Varma]: that that's had on the ground or the impact that's not had on the ground as it were.

00:46:19.140 --> 00:46:21.580
[Amit Varma]: And all your papers will, of course, be linked from the show notes.

00:46:21.580 --> 00:46:23.420
[Amit Varma]: So these will be available there.

00:46:23.420 --> 00:46:28.900
[Amit Varma]: And you say there are three features for the 2014 act, quote, one, the participatory mechanism

00:46:28.900 --> 00:46:35.380
[Amit Varma]: of TVCs, TVCs being town vending committees, decentralizes decision making from municipal

00:46:35.380 --> 00:46:39.660
[Amit Varma]: bodies to a committee of all stakeholders, including vendors, government officials and

00:46:39.660 --> 00:46:41.100
[Amit Varma]: resident associations.

00:46:41.100 --> 00:46:47.060
[Amit Varma]: The provision of 40% mandatory vendor representatives in the committee aims to ensure that their

00:46:47.060 --> 00:46:50.140
[Amit Varma]: interests are accommodated in their party to their own governance.

00:46:50.140 --> 00:46:56.700
[Amit Varma]: Two, until the survey and issuance of certificate of vending to all existing vendors is complete,

00:46:56.700 --> 00:46:58.100
[Amit Varma]: no vendor can be evicted.

00:46:58.100 --> 00:47:03.380
[Amit Varma]: TVCs are required to enumerate vendors every five years through safeguards and processes.

00:47:03.380 --> 00:47:08.300
[Amit Varma]: The law creates a permitting framework instead of a licensing regime.

00:47:08.300 --> 00:47:14.460
[Amit Varma]: And three, the act provides for an independent redressal committee to hear vendor grievances,

00:47:14.460 --> 00:47:15.460
[Amit Varma]: stop good.

